1
00:00:00,374 --> 00:00:01,754
Speaker 20: Hi, my name is Sergey.

2
00:00:02,704 --> 00:00:07,023
I'm a senior infrastructure platform
engineer at the Social Discovery Group.

3
00:00:07,774 --> 00:00:12,764
In this talk, I want to look at LLM
workloads from the infrastructure side.

4
00:00:13,264 --> 00:00:17,294
When teams move from experiments
to production, reliability is

5
00:00:17,294 --> 00:00:19,644
no longer only about the model.

6
00:00:20,124 --> 00:00:23,144
It also depends on the
Kubernetes platform.

7
00:00:23,644 --> 00:00:29,154
It depends on how workloads are scheduled,
how traffic moves through the network,

8
00:00:29,484 --> 00:00:35,034
how failure works, and how quickly we
can understand problems under load.

9
00:00:35,534 --> 00:00:41,474
My main point is simple: LLM services
become reliable only when the

10
00:00:41,644 --> 00:00:44,114
platform under them is reliable.

11
00:00:44,614 --> 00:00:48,094
LLM workloads make platform
weaknesses visible faster.

12
00:00:49,024 --> 00:00:51,994
They are different from
typical web services.

13
00:00:52,494 --> 00:00:55,443
A traditional web service
is usually CPU-based.

14
00:00:55,963 --> 00:01:00,133
Requests are short, and it's
often possible to scale the

15
00:01:00,143 --> 00:01:02,274
service by adding more replicas.

16
00:01:02,774 --> 00:01:06,754
LLM service depends on
expensive GPU capacity.

17
00:01:07,454 --> 00:01:13,664
They need a lot of memory, and requests
can run much longer Latency depends

18
00:01:13,694 --> 00:01:16,954
not only on the network or CPU.

19
00:01:17,414 --> 00:01:22,174
It also depends on model size,
prompt length, generated tokens,

20
00:01:22,234 --> 00:01:24,354
batching, and queue time.

21
00:01:24,854 --> 00:01:31,634
So infrastructure mistakes become
more visible, bad scheduling, unstable

22
00:01:31,634 --> 00:01:38,204
networking, or unexpected restarts can
quickly become user visible problems.

23
00:01:39,014 --> 00:01:41,784
Many LLM projects start as experiment.

24
00:01:42,044 --> 00:01:47,184
At that stage, it is normal to run
everything on one node, deploy manually,

25
00:01:47,883 --> 00:01:50,684
and debug problems directly on the server.

26
00:01:51,543 --> 00:01:54,134
But production changes the requirements.

27
00:01:54,834 --> 00:01:56,774
One node is no longer enough.

28
00:01:57,224 --> 00:01:59,714
One network path is no longer enough.

29
00:02:00,564 --> 00:02:02,904
Unexpected restarts become expensive.

30
00:02:03,404 --> 00:02:07,944
Default networking may work,
but when something breaks, it

31
00:02:07,944 --> 00:02:11,934
can be hard to understand where
the traffic actually goes.

32
00:02:12,434 --> 00:02:17,114
The problem is not that Kubernetes
cannot run LLM workloads.

33
00:02:17,614 --> 00:02:23,124
The problem is that production expose
weak assumption in the platform design.

34
00:02:23,824 --> 00:02:28,854
So before looking at the separate
components, let's start this

35
00:02:28,993 --> 00:02:31,204
simple reference arch-architecture.

36
00:02:32,033 --> 00:02:35,083
This is a simplified view of the platform.

37
00:02:35,974 --> 00:02:39,573
A user request enters through gateway API.

38
00:02:40,383 --> 00:02:45,483
Th-then it goes to an LLM
service running on GPU nodes.

39
00:02:46,203 --> 00:02:49,734
The service depends on model
storage or model cache.

40
00:02:50,724 --> 00:02:59,193
The whole path also depends on platform
services, monitoring, CI/CD, networking,

41
00:02:59,293 --> 00:03:01,353
and the Kubernetes control plane.

42
00:03:01,853 --> 00:03:07,923
The important point is that reliability
is not owned by one component.

43
00:03:08,673 --> 00:03:16,193
If gateway API, GPU scheduling, storage,
networking, or secrets are unstable,

44
00:03:16,573 --> 00:03:23,334
the LLM service become unstable too A
reliable LLM workloads need capacity and

45
00:03:23,354 --> 00:03:25,744
redundancy in different failure domains.

46
00:03:26,524 --> 00:03:30,774
Now we move from application
architecture to cluster architecture.

47
00:03:31,654 --> 00:03:35,694
For LLM workloads, failure
domains are very important.

48
00:03:36,384 --> 00:03:39,714
GPU nodes are expensive
and usually limited.

49
00:03:40,554 --> 00:03:46,124
If we lose one node, one switch,
or one rack, we can lose a large

50
00:03:46,154 --> 00:03:49,204
part of available GPU capacity.

51
00:03:50,164 --> 00:03:53,334
The control plane should
be also protected.

52
00:03:54,234 --> 00:03:59,544
etcd needs quorum, so control
plane nodes should be placed in

53
00:03:59,553 --> 00:04:02,154
separate physical failure domains.

54
00:04:02,934 --> 00:04:08,603
For GPU nodes, the goal is to
continue running or rescheduling

55
00:04:08,724 --> 00:04:11,014
workloads with predictable capacity.

56
00:04:11,914 --> 00:04:17,584
This means spreading replicas, avoiding
single network path, and keeping

57
00:04:17,584 --> 00:04:19,853
some spare capacity for failover.

58
00:04:20,334 --> 00:04:25,974
If the control plane is unstable, the
whole platform becomes harder to operate.

59
00:04:26,523 --> 00:04:30,933
The control plane is not used
for every user request, but it's

60
00:04:30,933 --> 00:04:33,144
critical for operating the platform.

61
00:04:33,644 --> 00:04:41,354
If the API server or etcd has problems,
scheduling, reload, and auto-scaling

62
00:04:41,474 --> 00:04:48,064
become unreliable this is especially
important for LLM workloads because

63
00:04:48,414 --> 00:04:51,704
GPU capacity is limited and expensive.

64
00:04:52,204 --> 00:04:58,614
In my preferred design, the Kubernetes
API endpoint uses a virtual IP.

65
00:04:59,294 --> 00:05:04,964
This virtual IP is announced
by BGP Anycast from all

66
00:05:04,974 --> 00:05:06,604
healthy control plane nodes.

67
00:05:07,104 --> 00:05:12,873
It's each node check its local API server.

68
00:05:13,373 --> 00:05:19,744
If the API server is healthy, the
node advertises the virtual IP.

69
00:05:20,513 --> 00:05:24,804
If it's not healthy, the
node removes the route.

70
00:05:25,674 --> 00:05:30,594
So the network sends API
traffic only to healthy nodes.

71
00:05:31,274 --> 00:05:39,324
This gives us active access to Kubernetes
API and simple network level failover.

72
00:05:39,824 --> 00:05:46,064
I also prefer BGP routing to run
on the host, not inside Kubernetes.

73
00:05:46,564 --> 00:05:47,694
The reason is simple.

74
00:05:48,044 --> 00:05:53,844
Kubernetes needs networking to start
pods, so basic networking should

75
00:05:53,854 --> 00:05:56,093
not depends on Kubernetes pods.

76
00:05:56,683 --> 00:06:01,834
For production, the network path
should be visible and predictable.

77
00:06:02,564 --> 00:06:08,104
In many default Kubernetes network
designs, the data path is hidden

78
00:06:08,104 --> 00:06:10,973
behind NAT or overlay encapsulation.

79
00:06:11,473 --> 00:06:16,314
This works, but during incidents it
can make troubleshooting much harder.

80
00:06:16,814 --> 00:06:22,664
We may see node IPs, translated
addresses or encapsulated traffic

81
00:06:22,684 --> 00:06:30,024
instead of the real pod-to-pod flow
In a routable design, pod CIDRs are

82
00:06:30,044 --> 00:06:32,424
known by the data center network.

83
00:06:33,234 --> 00:06:36,054
Traffic flows normal layer 3 routing.

84
00:06:36,554 --> 00:06:41,754
This makes the path easier to
understand with standard tools like

85
00:06:41,834 --> 00:06:44,924
iproute, traceroute, and tcpdump.

86
00:06:45,894 --> 00:06:53,264
For LLM services, this matters because
latency, packet loss, and network

87
00:06:53,314 --> 00:06:56,924
instability can directly affect users.

88
00:06:57,234 --> 00:07:02,524
In this network design, each
Kubernetes node peers with two

89
00:07:02,674 --> 00:07:05,224
top-of-rack switches using BGP.

90
00:07:05,724 --> 00:07:10,914
The node advertises its pod CIDR
into the data center fabric.

91
00:07:11,474 --> 00:07:18,293
Because of this, pod can be routed
dir- directly without overlay or NAT.

92
00:07:18,793 --> 00:07:23,744
ECMP allows both uplinks can
be used at the same time.

93
00:07:24,244 --> 00:07:29,693
This gives us not only redundancy, but
also active-active network capacity.

94
00:07:30,193 --> 00:07:32,743
BFD improves failure detection.

95
00:07:33,633 --> 00:07:41,783
If one link or one switch fails, BFD
helps BGP remove the failed path quickly

96
00:07:41,913 --> 00:07:44,783
instead of waiting for long BGP timers.

97
00:07:45,673 --> 00:07:51,573
I prefer running Bird on the host,
not as a Kubernetes pod, because

98
00:07:51,633 --> 00:07:55,293
routing is part of node bootstrap.

99
00:07:55,793 --> 00:07:59,194
It should not depend on
Kubernetes already being healthy.

100
00:08:00,034 --> 00:08:04,123
GPU nodes should be managed
as a platform infrastructure.

101
00:08:04,694 --> 00:08:10,744
Before we schedule LLM workloads GPU
nodes must be prepared correctly.

102
00:08:11,674 --> 00:08:17,103
It needs the correct NVIDIA driver
container runtime integration

103
00:08:17,463 --> 00:08:24,153
Kubernetes device plugin, node label,
monitoring, and a safe upgrade process.

104
00:08:25,023 --> 00:08:33,313
Kubernetes use device plugins to expose
special hardware like GPUs to the kubelet.

105
00:08:34,143 --> 00:08:40,373
After that, the cluster can expose
GPU resources In practice, many

106
00:08:40,413 --> 00:08:44,733
teams use the GPU NVIDIA operator.

107
00:08:45,553 --> 00:08:49,993
It can manage drivers, the
device plugin, container toolkit,

108
00:08:50,493 --> 00:08:52,713
node labeling, and monitoring.

109
00:08:53,213 --> 00:08:58,513
Kubernetes schedules GPU workloads
only when GPU resources are

110
00:08:58,543 --> 00:09:00,853
explicitly exposed and requested.

111
00:09:01,353 --> 00:09:06,453
Kubernetes doesn't schedule a
pod to a GPU au-automatically.

112
00:09:07,443 --> 00:09:14,253
The GPU must be exposed to Kubernetes,
usually by a device plug, plugin, and

113
00:09:14,273 --> 00:09:16,893
the pod must explicitly request it.

114
00:09:17,393 --> 00:09:21,503
For a simple service, a normal
deployment can be enough.

115
00:09:22,333 --> 00:09:28,713
Each replica request one GPU, and
Kubernetes schedules replicas only

116
00:09:28,753 --> 00:09:31,743
on nodes with available GPU capacity.

117
00:09:32,243 --> 00:09:37,673
For training, fine-tuning, or
batch workloads, a deployment is

118
00:09:37,863 --> 00:09:40,183
usually not the best abstraction.

119
00:09:41,153 --> 00:09:48,263
Jobs or queues are often a better
fit because these workloads

120
00:09:48,413 --> 00:09:54,123
are finite, expensive, and
need controlled concurrency.

121
00:09:54,623 --> 00:09:57,673
The operational point is simple.

122
00:09:58,483 --> 00:10:03,183
GPU capacity should be planned
and scheduled explicitly.

123
00:10:03,483 --> 00:10:08,913
Scheduling policy decides whether
GPU capacity is reliable or fragile.

124
00:10:09,413 --> 00:10:14,473
For GPU workloads, scheduling is
not only about finding any free node

125
00:10:15,213 --> 00:10:23,483
requests, tell Kubernetes how much CPU,
memory, and GPU capacity the pod needs.

126
00:10:23,983 --> 00:10:32,073
Node selectors or affinity help place for
LLM workloads on the correct node pool.

127
00:10:32,573 --> 00:10:38,663
Anti-affinity and topology spread
help avoid putting all replicas

128
00:10:38,703 --> 00:10:40,433
in the same failure domain.

129
00:10:40,933 --> 00:10:45,493
Taint and tolerations are
especially useful for GPU nodes.

130
00:10:45,993 --> 00:10:51,653
They prevent normal workload
from consuming resources

131
00:10:51,763 --> 00:10:53,873
on expensive GPU servers.

132
00:10:54,744 --> 00:11:00,773
At the same time, they allows
approved LLM workloads to run there.

133
00:11:01,273 --> 00:11:05,563
The goal is simple, use GPU
capacity efficiently, but

134
00:11:05,663 --> 00:11:08,503
not create fragile placement.

135
00:11:09,003 --> 00:11:15,353
One node, one rack, or one switch failure
should not take down the whole service.

136
00:11:16,033 --> 00:11:19,813
Reliable reload is part of
reliable infrastructure.

137
00:11:20,613 --> 00:11:24,503
For LLM services, reload
strategy is very important.

138
00:11:25,203 --> 00:11:30,973
A new model version, prompt template,
runtime image, or configuration can

139
00:11:30,973 --> 00:11:34,703
change latency, cost, and error rate.

140
00:11:35,203 --> 00:11:39,493
Gateway API gives us a clean
way to manage external traffic.

141
00:11:40,213 --> 00:11:46,593
With HTTP route, we can split traffic
between two versions of the service.

142
00:11:47,093 --> 00:11:54,343
For example ninety percent of traffic
can stay on stable version, and ten

143
00:11:54,343 --> 00:11:56,733
percent can go to the new version.

144
00:11:57,173 --> 00:12:00,433
If metrics looks good, we
increase the percentage.

145
00:12:00,953 --> 00:12:06,313
If something goes wrong, rollback
can be done by shifting traffic back.

146
00:12:07,293 --> 00:12:09,163
The last point is observability.

147
00:12:09,663 --> 00:12:14,553
For LLM services, it's not enough
to measure only application errors.

148
00:12:15,243 --> 00:12:21,613
We also need to see GPU utilization,
GPU memory, pod scheduling problems,

149
00:12:21,743 --> 00:12:28,663
network behavior, GPU state, API
server latency, and etcd health.

150
00:12:29,163 --> 00:12:31,113
The final checklist is simple.

151
00:12:31,713 --> 00:12:39,093
Make the network path visible, keep
the control plane stable, plan GPU

152
00:12:39,093 --> 00:12:46,583
scheduling, use a safe reload strategy,
and collect metrics before production.

153
00:12:47,083 --> 00:12:51,003
The model is important, but
the platform decides how the

154
00:12:51,003 --> 00:12:53,413
model behaves under failure.

155
00:12:53,913 --> 00:12:54,983
That's it for today.

156
00:12:55,283 --> 00:12:56,523
Thank you for listening.

